ame>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF035039%2F1"><gtr:id>BF2BAF50-9A1C-46A6-851E-6939D1EC3182</gtr:id><gtr:title>Sociological perspectives on the social, political and ethical role of translators and translation in contact zones of conflict</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F035039/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>During the three year period of this research fellowship, a range of scholarly activities will be pursued leading to a stronger conceptualisation of translation as a socially embedded activity.&amp;nbsp; Sociological perspectives on translation constitute a new and significant direction for work in the field of translation and a potential shift in the relationship between this field and the social sciences. The work undertaken over the three years will contribute to the further theoretical and methodological development of a sound sociological approach to translation studies.&amp;nbsp; Particular focus will be given to the role of translators and interpreters working in contexts of geo-political significance and to the relationship between translation, ethics, culture and politics. &amp;nbsp;
&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;
&lt;br />A number of specific objectives will be undertaken toward the realisation of these aims. These include: a book-length study of the social, cultural and ethical dimensions of the role of translators and interpreters working in situations of political conflict; an exploratory study of the training of translators working with peacekeeping or combat forces in military contexts in order to develop theory and inform training practices more broadly; and a book dedicated to the exploration of the origins and development of sociological approaches in translation and interpreting research. &amp;nbsp;
&lt;br />
